description:
In 2014 two dutch girls went missing while visiting the boquete region of panama. Months later remains of the two dutch girls were found scattered all around the culebra river, but the strange thing was - their possessions were found neatly presented on a nearby rock. 

How and why the dutch girls went missing is still unknown but stay with me as I tell you the story and then examine the evidence to see what really happened to Lisanne Froon and Kris Kremers, did they succumb to an accident? or were they murdered? 

#truecrime #unsolvedmystery

comments.text: Great video on this disappearance case, and thank you for the special thanks at the start of your video Nice how you illustrated things and the suspense you created
comments.author: @scarletr.7753

comments.text: Youtube creators all seem to cover the same few cases, but this is the most in depth video I've seen on this case. Terrifying.
comments.author: @RationalGaze216

comments.text: I live in Panama and this is my recommendation, never, EVER get on taxi when there is another guy already inside, even  if you are with a girlfriend. Take the metro or bus, its safer. If you are in a hurry, call an uber. They have the drivers information registered. Anyone can get a taxi license this days. Also always pay attention to body language of the people you interact with, if you feel something is not right,  there is a reason for it. Maybe Im paranoid but I'm always checking my surroundings.

They had nothing with them, nothing to make clean water, no food, no hatchet to make a shelter, no dry clothes no compass and no map, among other things. So if the evidence shows that they were alive for longer then a week, in my opinion someone kept them alive. Just based on survival chances and not including all the other evidence. comments.text:
I'm really, really thankful for this in-depth analysis that shines light on the possibility of foul play. Whenever there is a disappearance and people don't have an immediate answer, they're too quick to say, "oh just an accident." However, I'm glad that this video makes it clear that it could have been an accident or it could have not been one at all. The man interviewed around roughly 30 mins does an excellent job of highlighting the suspicion of a single deleted photo. As he so cleverly notes, if you're lost in the woods and desperate, the last thing you're doing is going far out of your way to delete a single photo. Heck, I personally rarely delete photos because if they're garbage they're garbage. The piece about the rolled-up skin is also an important reason for pause. And the shorts too and other details ... well, you get the point. Anyway, altogether an in-depth and just analysis. Thank you for your upload.

I remember hearing about the true crime Smiley Face murders where all the evidence points towards murder but police keep denying that anything sinister may be going on. I think we need to wonder, in this case too, whether police or authorities are covering things up due to corruption or fears of losing tourism revenues, mitigating the chances of a lawsuit, etc. I wish someone would interview all the tour guides, surrounding locals, and even police in great detail.

Firstly, Peaked Interest I feel compelled to thank you for the humanity and respect that you gave to the girls and their loved ones in your brilliant analysis of this tragic case - so different to the usual sensationalist, dehumanised  stuff that litters YouTube. 
This story has moved me immensely, and I strongly feel that Lisanne and Kris will want their loved one to know, whatever they need to know - to get some form of closure, and if there is evidence out there I believe someone somewhere will have an insight revealed to them to bring it to light and answers found - and that isn't just sentimentalist woowoo wishful thinking.
As an aside, I am a late in life (now 70) British male solo traveller/backpacker/adventure seeker (therefore your opening few words had me laughing out loud in the context of my age !) and have now changed my plans from a return trip to Cambodia to - would you believe Panama and in particular Boquete :) next year. I am a low budget hostel and street food guy and fully endorse your comment about taxis and would add that what keeps me out of trouble is to dress down + cheap watch, tatty smart phone and buddy up for any drinking forays - and especially practice observation and awareness skills (equally important at home too) AND FFS listen to your deep down gut 
feelings at all times.
Thanks again for a great video - respect

comments.text:
What a captivating, immersive video mate, very well done. As a Dutchie myself and someone who loves unsolved mysteries, this case has always struck with me and kept my attention through the years. This video showed me more unheard details than all the other ones around. Great job on the research. 

I must admit that I have always thought this was an accident of two girls just being terribly unprepared and naive of their surroundings. They misjudged the trail because why would they only take one bottle of water for the 2 of them for a supposedly 6 hour hike? Supposedly they wanted to visit a waterfall that was off route and thats where the trouble started. They couldnt find the location, noticed it was getting dark, wanted to turn around but got lost, panicked, one of the girls eventually fell and got hurt, the other one eventually went back on her own etc. etc. 
But then you come to the backpack and the bone findings and all of that kind of goes out the window right. 

Tour guide F becomes awfully suspicious after having seen your video. I feel like the cab driver might have contacted F after he dropped them off and he took care of the rest. Hence why he was killed later because he could snitched to anyone about this. 

And then the report of the girl that, 4 years later, went to the same exact place and same exact guide as these girls, just wow. She is lucky to be still alive. 

I can't wait for the Netflix documentary about this one.

comments.text: What I didn't catch you mention about the tour guide is one thing about guilty parties - they involve themselves as much as possible in the case. This can be done for various reasons. One is to keep abreast of the investigation - what is found, what investigators know, how close they are to evidence or potentially solving the case. Two is because they enjoy seeing the fruits of their crime play out - the investigators squirming for answers - they get a sense of superiority from outsmarting, if you will, the investigators. Everything I have heard and read on this case circumstantially points to the tour guide. I would have focused my investigation on him, his coffee farm, employees that could have conspired out of fear of him & I would have interviewed in a formal setting as many of his tour guide customers, particularly female ones, as possible. My suspicion is that he told them where to go because he knew the area intimately & then at some point killed them, probably at his coffee farm, took those pictures, deleted an incriminating one, & that he himself was the one "attempting" to dial emergency services in an area he knew wouldn't have proper coverage. He did all this to support the narrative that the two were lost. He then later could easily place some remains, their backpack in various areas going unnoticed to further support this narrative. I believe he would have PC's at his coffee farm - whether for inventory, receipts or whatever else related to running this farm - and would have deleted an incriminating photo, that perhaps would have linked him to the crime. I don't believe they were ever lost out in the jungle for a week, they were probably held for days, then killed. As a final note about the incorrect password usage - I would be willing to bet the girls knew each others phone passwords because they were very close friends and also because they were traveling & just in case of an emergency either one could use either phone. They were rather prepared and intelligent young women, they would have thought of this. Who wouldn't know the password? The tour guide.

comments.text: My unique idea - I think the first part of the hike was very pleasant very happy. However I think its possible that F then stayed around the area to if others are going on the same path. Once he understood that no more hikers were coming he then quickly race to the girls but made it seem as if it was a pure coincidence that he was also walking through at that time. He then offered to show the girls his farm in the middle of the forest and probably claimed that there was some good scenery to take photos. This is potentially proven by the change in behaviour in the photos naturally when youre with a friend or someone you know you can be yourself you can smile you can laugh. However when does the third-party that that you are not familiar with or is a stranger to you you start to act shy reserved and youre often careful of how you behave. The missing picture is between the daytime and the night time- The last photos are taken of one girl only. Its impossible to determine whether they have a girl took the photo or whether it was F when they were on their way to the middle of the jungle so that he could show them his farm. This wouldve been a good technique to prove to the girls that he was just being friendly while allowing them to the middle of the jungle by offering to take pictures of them on the way.  The missing photo 509 could be one of two things the first possibility could be that it was a picture of both of the girls this would prove that there was a third-party with them and therefore is deleted because it clearly shows that someone else was there and the second theory would be one of the photos was taken of F and one of the other girls by the other girl this would then put him at the scene. If his intention was to lead them into the middle of the jungle it wouldve been difficult for him to give a reason why he didnt want to be in any photos and him being in a photo with the girls would have only made them trust him more. Also I would like to know but its impossible to determine the circumstance in which 911 or 112 was dialled. We often see that emergency numbers are dialled when not in obvious panic. If the girls suspected that F was getting awkward or there was a uneasy feeling its quite possible that they could have dialled it secretly. Hence the gaps in calls. Although gaps in calls could symbolise the need to preserve battery it could also show that they were trying to call in secret while with a third-party for example one of the girls was distracting him while another girl was trying to secretly dial 112 so that the authorities would know that there is something going on - in hopes that the authorities would be able to secretly listen to the conversation maybe while the phone was in the pocket and determine the location where they were. Ultimately I believe at one point F wanted a sexual favour in which the girls declined and run or there was a plan folder together when things started to go wrong where the girls would go run. This then causes the girls to hide in shallow ditches through the forest or behind trees in which they made panic calls to 911. When you are hiding and when you are running from somebody you have no time to to text or record a final message. With residents saying that they had scrims from the forest this could possibly be because a machete was used to run off to the girls or one of the girls was slaughtered hence the screams. Is also possible that one girl was killed and another girl was then taken to a secret spot in the forest and raped and then kept alive and slowly over the days was was cut with the machete which would explain the fresh skin because skin does not compose if the person is alive. It is also quite possible that somewhere in the forest one of the girls could be tied up or chained up without a leg and with skin cut of her.

comments.text:
This video was definitely one of the best and most nuanced one Ive seen on the case so far.  I personally still flip flop between what I believe happened to them to be honest because while theres a lot of weird, nonsensical parts to it that dont really fit with a lost hiker, theres also a lot of parts that dont really mesh with the idea of it being a crime either.  A lot of the stuff that people point to as evidence of wrongdoing can be fairly simply explained as not being suspicious, but there are definitely a few little things that make me raise an eyebrow too.

The part I have a hard time justifying with the idea of them being simply lost is the fact that no one was able to trace them at any point during the search, not even so much as a broken branch, or anything of theirs left behind until suddenly months later there stuff is so easily discoverable.  The missing photo, the decomp, all that other stuff I can fairly easily rationalize because of how peculiar things like that behave in a jungle environment, but the fact that there was no inkling of them at all during such an insanely large and thorough search is kinda baffling to me.  Idk, I doubt well ever truly find out what happened though in any case sadly.

comments.text:
Hace un tiempo vi este video y me parecio muy bien hecho, siendo objetivo sin inclinarse de forma tajante a una sola teora.  Ahora aos despus que hay disponible ms informacin sobre el caso, sigue siendo un buen video por muchos puntos entre ellos el anlisis que realizas sobre los restos seos. 

Algo que me a llamado la atencin es que muchos aseguran que la pelvis de Kris estaba "rota", es decir fracturada. Esto no correcto, hasta donde se, en el informe forense no se menciona fractura alguna en este hueso (solo hace mencin a fractura en 3 metatarsianos del pie izquierdo de Lisanne). Una fractura de alto impacto como una pelvica es un hallazgo muy relevante que jamas se omitiria en un informe. Por lo tanto este hueso esta desarticulado del sacro posteriormente y de la sinfsis del pbis anteriormente, esto muy probablemente fue postmorten ya que si fuese durante un accidente (caida de altura, golpe directo) existiran evidencias de esto en el hueso coxal izquierdo (fracturas, avulsiones seas, fisuras) nada de esto se menciona en alguna parte. (Soy mdico).
El otro resto de Kris es una costilla, cuya apariencia a sido motivo de controversia.

De Lisanne se menciona fractura (al parecer simple) de 3 metatarsianos de pie izquierdo. Tambien periostitis tibial izquierda (esto es un proceso inflamatorio por sobre uso muscular, no es infeccioso, no confundir con osteomieltis). Del femr izquierdo, perone y rotula izquierda (se recupero su extremidad inferior izquierda completa) no se menciona lesin alguna. Esto ultimo da mucha duda razonable para cuestionar que las fracturas metatarsianas sean debidas a caida de altura (ya que se podria esperiar dado el caso, fracturas en femr o tobillo que son ms comunes). El mecanismo ms tipico de las fracturas metatarsianos son: un golpe directo, tiron brusco o torsin).
Con estos restos seos no hay forma alguna de determinar causas de muerte, ni permite descartar o asegurar la implicacin de un juego sucio. 

Me da la impresin de que se desconoce informacin sobre el informe forense, deberia haber ms detalles. Tengo entendido que el hueso coxal izquierdo tenia marcas de raices y impresiones dentales de posibles roedores. Pero del femr, tibia o perone de LF no  se menciona rastro alguno de carroa o erosiones por rocas que cabria de esperar por el lugar donde se encontraron (en y en los alrededores de un rio muy muy rocoso con aguas poco profundas). No se si solo es algo de omisin. 

Dicho rio rocoso donde estaban esparcidos los restos, cuando lo visualizas, es un sitio donde no esperarias que algo recorriera mucha distancia sin quedar atrapado entre las rocas. Que el pie izquierdo de LF estubiera separado por kilometros de distancia del resto de su miembro inferior izquierdo que estaban ms al norte, es llamativo! Podria pensarse en algn animal, pero si en el informe forense no se menciona signos de carroa en estos restos, crea la duda.

comments.text:
What I find very strange about this case are the photos. At one point, they are smiling and enjoying their trip together at every photo they take, even when only one of them is being photographed by the other. But then suddenly Kris is being photographed from a far distance. 

She has a different facial expression. What suddenly changed that she's not smiling anymore? 

She carried a bottle of a water with her. Why did she carry the bottle if they had a backpack? Why would she wanna carry a bottle of water with her while walking through such a hard terrain? 

Why would Lisanne photograph Kris when she was turned back? I would understand that if the photos were taken on an i-Phone. When you photograph on an i-Phone you usually don't care what you document because later the photos can be easily organized and deleted. But when you have a camera, it's a different experience. First of all, the process of taking photos isn't that fast as it is on a phone (especially in 2014 with an older technology) so you think about what you photograph. Second of all, it's annoying going through every single photo later and check whether you like them or not so you don't take random photos at a place where's basically nothing. Third, this was a jungle, their hands were probabaly sweating and they must've been tired. Why would they photograph if they didn't have to? Forth, those are young girls we talk about. I'm a girl and we usually care about how we look, what and why we photograph, we want to give emotions, meaning and story to a photo. I would never photograph my friend turned back on a camera because there isn't a usual reason for it. 

Why didn't Kris stop and take a photo of Lisanne as well? At every place they took a photo it was both of them who were there. Suddenly it's only Kris at several photos. 

Why would they take 10 of 100 photos on April 1st, then 7 days nothing and then 90 photos during night on April 8th?

comments.text:
Ive always thought that the guide was extremely suspicious. Why would he go to their room the next day, only because they hadnt met him as scheduled? That makes zero sense. The normal thing to do would have been to call them, and if he didnt even try to call them, thats not normal. 

If  tourists dont show up for a guided tour, the  tour guide might try to call, but if they cant get through, they shrug their shoulders and would then go about his or her day. Who would go to where they were staying and GET KEYS to enter their room-and snoop around it for a half hour? 

They were obviously young, naive and an easy target. If someone knew where to look for them on the trail, they would have been convenient prey. It seems very unlikely that so many things went wrong and this  was all coincidental. 

Later, finding the backpack with their things still conveniently in it in working condition is too bizarre. The phones, and then the camera and that one  missing photo, randomly deleted is absolutely  suspect. The weird way that their bone fragments were located, plus Lissanes skin being found later on, all fails to add up. 

I dont think that 2 young girls, ill equipped for a long hike and who were  unfamiliar with their surroundings would have been tempted to go off trail so far into the jungle unless something/someone was pursuing them.  They were trying for get away from something and it wasnt an accidental mistake. 

The cover up has been filled with red herrings and senseless information to throw people off, like the dog Blue, who is in none of the pictures, and probably didnt join them. The cab driver saying that he dropped them off so late in the day also doesnt make sense. I dont think they would start a hike that late when they had no idea how long it might take to get there and back-especially dressed as they were, without jackets or extra clothing, 

The ONLY logical conclusion to me is that they were pursued and subsequently caught and the evidence that turned up later was all planted. Its very horrible and sad. but I dont believe that they wandered around for 10 days and then took a bunch of weird pictures but never thought of writing goodbye text messages to their parents or friends. The picture of Kris hair was probably taken by someone else after she was dead. RIP Kris & Lissane! Im sorry that we dont know what happened, but it definitely is not the official story

comments.text:
Excellent video! My theory is that their captor(s) didn't realize the women still had their cell phones, so the women had to be discreet about when they attempted to call for help and do it when their captors weren't looking. This would explain why they only checked their phones or attempted to call 911 during daylight hours as lighting up their phones at night would be more noticeable. It also explains why they never checked their phones or attempted to call at exactly the same time (probably one of them was talking to / distracting their captor(s) while the other attempted it). It might explain why Froon left her phone on all night on April 2-3 and wasted so much precious battery; she almost got caught and had to stow the phone without turning it off. From April 5 onward, Kremers was either dead or incapacitated, while Froon's phone was out of power; hard to say whether it was Froon trying to operate Kremers' phone without knowing her PIN, or whether their captors had finally discovered the phones and wanted to see what was on the phones. 

Me personally, if I was lost in the wild, I'd probably be attempting to get a signal and call for help every hour on the hour for the first day before I'd start doing it more sporadically to conserve battery. Something or someone was preventing them from calling for help more often. 

By April 8th, I think the captors had realized they f'ed up, that "missing pretty white woman" is a thing and the heat was on and a 6'0" tall white woman plus a 5'7"/5'8" white woman weren't going to just vanish without anyone noticing, so they shot all of the nighttime photos to make it look like the women had gotten lost. This included a staged toilet paper / mirror SOS photo. They planted the backpack and the bone fragments when they felt safe to do so, that way people would say, "Case closed, they got lost in the jungle" and stop looking for them.

comments.text:
Ladies, please always carry pepper spray. I've been to and am planning to move to Panama. I had a strange experience in Boquette. I was on a tour back in 2018, after the tour some of us stayed on for a few days to explore Boquette. One night we met at a restaurant and had a wonderful steak dinner. They (all couples) left in cabs, and I thought i would walk back to the the Airbnb studio I had rented, about eight blocks away. Then I thought what am I doing, I am in a foreign country, don't speak Spanish, and I had better call a cab/taxi, by now the others, all couples, had left in cabs back to their respective hotels. I asked the young lady who had called cabs for the others, to call a cab for me, but alas all the cabs had gone in for the night.  It was now about 10 p.m.  One of the waiters overheard the conversation, and told me his brother was waiting for him outside, but he had to wash some dishes before he could leave, so his brother could take me and I could pay him $5.  I said okay, as I would be "home" in five or less minutes.       
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             Well, I got in the brother's car, and he took off. I told him I was going to the town center, and he said okay. The town center was straight ahead, but he bore left at the fork and was proceeding along the way.  All of a sudden he turned behind a tall dark building, and the hairs at the back of my neck stood up on edge and I said in the sternest voice, "If you do not get me to where I need to go, I will tear your nuts off!". He then replied, "Okay, I know where you are going," and one minute later we were at the town center.                                                                                                '
I did not sleep very well night, I could have easily been a victim to an attack or worse, foul play. I who am always watching Investigative Discovery, and thinking that could never happen to me. One never knows. I am happy that I had walked around the neighborhood during the day, and I knew where I was staying, and how to get there. Now if only I had some pepper spray........ I thought I was safe. He had told me he lived on the Caribbean side of Panama. The thing was we were leaving the next day. I was travelling by myself, no one would have missed me, they would have assumed that I had missed my flight. Scareeeeeeee!!!

comments.text:
The pictures of Kris being further away are pretty normal to me. I can relate to the framing of the photo as my friend being further up the track and me standing back and taking in the surroundings, capturing them wandering around the environment. I feel like as they wandered further in the jungle, the track becomes narrow and usually somebody has to lead and another follows. They might have just been stopping to look at things, maybe one was slower than the other... I don't think it's that out of the ordinary. And Kris' expression just looks neutral and like they're exploring. MAYBE at this stage they are starting to get a bit unnerved because they've lost their way/ deviated from the track? But not yet fearful as it's still light out... Idk. Or if your stalker hypothesis is to be the case, maybe their high energy and good spirits have kind of dissipated and they're just starting to become aware of a potential pursuit... Capturing Kris may have been a way to have evidence of their whereabouts?
Also the bras could have just been taken off because they were uncomfortable. But also the swimming theory makes sense too. 
I think that review is incredibly troubling though. The threat he made is so unsettling, especially considering the state the remains were found in. And his involvement in this case..... Yeah I'm actually very suspicious. 
Putting in all that time to help the search is actually just a really easy way to serve his innocence if he was involved. He knows the area as well. It wouldn't strike me as something that was THAT far out of his capacity. If he's worked there so long, built a business in that environment, surely poor weather conditions are not something he hasn't dealt with before in that jungle...
ALSO i just thought about it. It would make sense if he left all the possessions. If he runs a coffee farm and has so much tourism.. he is probably fairly wealthy. To avoid foul play suspicion, leaving behind all the belongings intact would throw the scent off any third party involvement. I'm very curious as to what he did in those girls rooms for half an hour... Police should have searched him...

comments.text: I really enjoyed your analysis of the evidence. It was well-thought, well-reasoned, and objective. The biggest question for me is the state of the remaining bones and tissue. I understand some bones were separated. What body parts/sections were found intact? In what position? And were skulls found? Could they have detected any chemical/artificial bleaching through testing? The mere question surrounding photo 509 establishes foul play. Photo 509 could only have been deleted manually with a computer that had specialized software. Ergo, either the perp(s) happened to have a charged laptop with this software on their person; or, the memory card was taken, the photo deleted, and the card returned to the camera in the backpack in the jungle; or, the photo was deleted after discovery. Deletion after discovery seems the most probable. Especially when you consider the fact that they framed what is clearly probable homicide as nothing more than a tragic drowning accident. comments.text: I know I'm commenting WAY late, but I'd be interested to know your thoughts on the following theory that wasn't covered. I know this case quite well and I think you did a particularly good job covering it - definitely learned new details, personally - but my initial thought, as a woman, was that perhaps one of the girls injured herself enough that she was unable to walk. Rather than leave her friend alone in the jungle, the other girl remained with her, expecting help to arrive while also attempting to call emergency services for help. At some point, they may have decided to leave the trail, perhaps to find water, and became lost. They then did what all young people are told to do when lost: remain in that place and wait for help. This would explain why they were conserving battery life on the phones and only using them at regularly timed intervals. At some point, the injured girl died. Her friend, likely dehydrated and not thinking straight, was likely no longer in any condition to travel and chose to keep waiting for help, at last succumbing herself. This could explain why, once one phone died, the other continued to be used but the password wasn't known by the friend. While the camera and phone use support this theory, I now believe your abduction theory makes much more sense, given that their bag was found in pristine condition with the camera and phones inside. Perhaps the phones turning on at consistent times was done when their captor was away. It is frustrating that we will probably never know for sure, but your final theory that it could have been the tour guide is very compelling.

comments.text:
I'm not saying this isn't foul play, but people don't give nature enough credit. 

1 girl breaks her leg or ass on the hike, which is the one holding the camera. The other one is far away and ahead because they're scouting a route for the injured girl to take while the other hobbled along behind. 

Eventually the pain is too much or shock sets in due to the injury and weather/wet (cold and wet overnight or from river may be hypothermia), and the one holding the camera passes out, begins going semi conscious, or dies. 

The other girl brings the body or helps the possibly semi conscious one walk. Cellphone dies, so tries to unlock other friends phone. Continues to try calling emergency services. 

7 days of all night use a flashlights batteries will die. The camera is then used to navigate using flash as the second girl continues to try to escape. This kills the battery on the camera. Unclear if she left the body of the other girl or not. The back of the head photo leads me to think she was alone and was checking for an injury back there by taking the picture. Hair is relatively clean after 7 days, especially if it gets wet. 

Final girl losing consciousness and stumbles off a bridge or slips from a rock, breaking herself and drowning.  Backpack and shorts wash up immediately, shorts either came off in the flowing river due to weightloss pass 8 days or scavengers. Digital camera was found by woman. Probably poor woman who kept it for a while for herself, which is why she had it. Free back pack full of free stuff, probably just stole it, until she saw about the missing girls on TV. At which point she turned it in. Simple petty theft of unclaimed item in the woods. Digital camera will definitely work if it was turned off and battery was dead when it got wet, then dried completely before being turned on, which is likely. 

Girls are dead. The innumerable ways a body decomposes in the wild and the bugs weather etc present too many variables. We will never know why all of the bones were found the way they were. Fish and water especially can clean a bone. Scavengers and birds particularly will carry bones great distances, hence the spread. However, if sealed in a boot, tightly laced, and leather, will keep predators out. Surprisingly a lot of animals won't fight to get meat out of boots due to smell and taste of the leather. Which is what hiking boots are made of. If the laces are tight they will eat to the ridge and leave the rest, giving the impression of a clean cut. 

 We all saw the avg monthly payment of people there. That tour guide cared because he wanted the money for the tour. He may have tried to steal some money to make up for the loss of the tour when visiting the girls room, explaining the 30 min in there. But nothing was taken anyway. Then there is a reward worth more than several months of work, of course he's scouring the woods. He knows them like the back of his hand. He's fairly confident he can find them and get the money. Which he does. 

All of this is in light detail I don't want to type it all and rife with grammatical and spelling errors sorry. Again I'm not saying it's not foul play; But an accident, naivety, greed, and more innocent petty crimes could be the issue.

comments.text: When I first started looking into this case, my initial conclusion was that they succumbed to the Jungle they were lost in. If I had to guess, I was concluding that one of the girls died before the other due to a poisoned snake bite. Panamas Jungles are home to about 26 poisonous snake species. The Ferdelance, Corals, and vipers just to name a few. I thought they got lost and at nightfall it was harder to see and one of the girls got bit and died. The other girl naturally in a state of shock and morally unable to leave her deceased friend frantically tried calling for help before and after her friends snake bite. Eventually the 2nd girl ended up dying of dehydration and other jungle elements. I mustve been in denial because I wanted to believe so bad that something sinister didnt happen. After getting all the evidence (or from what we know) the unsettling series of events and things not adding up there is absolutely no doubt in my mind there was foul play.

comments.text: This is one of the best video I have seen on this endless riddle, thank you so much for such quality work. I just wanted to point out that the piece of rolled-up skin turned out to be animal, probably a cow's skin. Something I hardly ever see is regarding Kris's shorts: if we accept the idea the women might have taken their bras off to go for a swim, it will make sense to take off shorts in denim, which is a very densely woven fabric, and is difficult to get dry again and, if worn while wet, would definitely be uncomfortable, to say the least. If we suppose the girls have indeed taken a dip in the river and taken their bras off in that respect, then it would make sense Kris would take off her shorts as well, as she knew she had at least 3/4 hours of pretty intense walk through the cloud jungle, with a lot of altitude change, and being tired of having already walked their way to the Mirador, with the possibility to have to walk further on the Serpent trail. Since they had no spare clothes, nothing to dry themselves with, no waterproof clothes, no jacket, no tent, hammock or anything to protect themselves from the unforgiving jungle and mosquitoes, spiders, snakes, birds or big cats and any hostile faunae, wearing wet (and I mean absolutely wet through, if they have a swim, it wouldn't be wet from the rain, from slipping and falling in a puddle, or just from the ambient atmosphere in the jungle, as it's literally a cloud forest, with clouds literally being in the jungle and hikers having to walk through it) denim shorts would be an actual risk of hypothermia, as we must assume that that swim must have been pretty close in time from the night falling, as the night falls earlier inside the jungle, due to the dense vegetation. What I never see questioned, is what happened to Lisanne's clothes? She was wearing clothes as well, obviously. What happened to Kris' top, and her hiking boots? To Lisanne's other hiking boots? Also, what keeps on bothering me, is when they found the bones of Lisanne and Kris (the tibia, femur of Lisanne, the pelvic and rib bone off Kris) were the bones of, depending on the sources, from 3 to 5 other people. Do we have to assume everybody seems to just drop dead at this exact spot, but in a way that only partial remains are found as well? I don't want to sound conspiractionist, but it feels more logical that it's some sort of dumping ground of some sort more than a place where the bones of people dying in the river seem to find their way at this spot only, with Lisanne's foot still whole, with the shoe and the lace still tied, with skin in early stages of decomposition? (Some other content creator actually showed the foot outside the shoe, and fair enough I'm not a doctor or an expert, but it's kind of green/greyish in colour, and clearly looks like it hasn't been decomposing in the jungle for more than 10 weeks? What about the anonymous tip that 2 skeletons were seen on the Culebra river banks ? What about Osman's picture taken on the 1st of April 2014 around 4/4:30 pm, showing Osman, another gang member of Henry Gonzales's (Feliciano's stepson)'s gang, and what looks like 2 white women, one brunette taller than the other woman, with striking redish hair, saved under the name Criss*? Osman told his mum the gang was about to shmurder him because he knew what happened to *las holandesas (the Dutch women) and not only he is found dead in a body of water the 4th of April, with a blow at the head, but his funerals were disturbed by gang members. The taxi driver who dropped the women at the beginning of the Pianista trail changed his version twice, then said he feared for his life regarding the Dutch Women, then is found dead about a year after Lisanne and Kris have gone missing. Another gang member told Osman's mother he wanted to confess about what happened to the women and why Osman was found dead, he just wanted to celebrate his 23rd birthday first, then confessing everything to her. He was killed by a hit and run on the night of his birthday. What if picture 509 was a picture of Lisanne and/or Kris at the Hot Springs, therefore proving the women haven't got lost on the hike, but actually finished the trail safely and unharmed, as multiple witnesses have said to have seen the women on their way back from the hike, but for some reason (looks at the corrupted Panamean government, remember the Panamean Papers scandal? and the multi million, maybe billions tourism industry?) have all been dismissed and never investigated? How about Edwin's (member of Henry Gonzalez' gang) red truck spotted by multiple witnesses on the Pianista that day? there's a theory that says Kris and Lisanne finished their hike safe and sound, and at the end of the trail were the gang (Edwin, Henry, Osman...) in the red truck, offering them a ride to show them the Hot Springs. The women knew the men, having talked to them and accepted rides in the red truck before (as multiple witnesses have stated): on the picture of Kris and Lisanne having brunch at the Boquete caf (owner being Edwin's family) , when you see Lisanne's picture at the Sabroson caf having brunch , you can actually see the red truck in the background. The Hot Springs are about 45 minutes drive from Il Pianista trail, and that's why the first 112 calls have been made: Lisanne and Kris started to fear that the men were not taking them to the Hot Spring and started being fearful for their safety. When arrived, picture 509 is taken, maybe of Kris and/or Lisanne at the Hot Spring having a swim, and another picture is taken using Osman's phone. Then, the men offered the women to go party at Edwin's house, in the jungle, located on an alternative trail near the Pianista (you start hiking the Pianista, then you need to get off the trail to find this unmarked trail) but, fuelled by alcohol and drugs, Henry would have tried to have sexual intercourse with Kris, who would have slapped him in the face. Henry, not only humiliated to be slapped by a woman, but also enraged, would have hit Kris with his fists. Lisanne would have tried to stop him, and would have been hit by a hammer. Then, in a puddle of blood, the gang members would have rped the women and shmurdered them. The calls made after the 1st of April would be stagged, just like the night pictures of the 8th: no need to go deep into the jungle, just going in Edwin's backgarden was enough. As the investigation was not only stopping, but growing in intensity, the backpack would have been dropped , just like a few bones and Lisanne's foot, practically in Feliciano's backgarden, as he owns a farm in Alto Romero. This way, the families would know their daughter are dead, the investigation stops, as even the government was keen to say it was just a tragic accident of 2 ill-prepared foreigners who were not prepared for the terrain on the Serpent trail, and the indigenous people willing to say they discovered the backpack were hoping to get the 30K offered by the family for any information helping finding their daughter. When you remember Feliciano, Henry's step dad, was inside Kris and Lisanne's home alone on the 2nd of April, before anyone even suspected something happened (so far, the host family noticed they didn't come back, but simply assumed they stayed with friends or partied) without any witness or police presence for about half an hour, it leaves him time to arrange some clothes and other stuff to make it look like they never came back from their hike, left his visit card on the bed, etc. He also is the one who reported them missing, organised search parties on the Pianista trail. It's him and his team who found their remains, the bones, the foot ... and it was very close from his property in Alto Romero. Say if he was aware of anything bad that happened to them, and would have wanted to take the focus of Henry, he wouldn't have done any different or better. See the YouTube channel of Scarlett R. and her review of Lost In Panama podcast, and the Lost in Panama podcast itself is available on Apple , Spotify and all other major podcasts broadcasters. If I do find that staging the calls and night pictures are an extra step that is extremely rarely seen in shmurder cases, it still make more sense than the official Panamean explanation that they would have fallen from a monkey bridge (cable bridge made of3 cables, 2 for each hand and the other one to walk on, extremely dangerous even for the natives who are used to it) and their bodies would be at the bottom of the Culebra river. With Lisanne's foot finding its way out of the river she has fallen in, to go behind a tree, with other fragments of her leg bone and Kris' half pelvic bone, one rib, and the bones of at least 3 other unknown people. Whatever you look at it, whether they got lost and/or injured and wandered the jungle for at least 10 days (as the last phone activity was the 11th of April) or what I described, it must have been extremely scary, and the most horrible way to die that those two young women didn't deserve (not that anybody deserves any of the scenario as a way to pass, but you get the idea). May they rest in peace, and I hope some day her families and us, the general public, will know what happened to these ladies who just wanted to travel, have a holiday and help the local children, as patronising as it may sound.

comments.text: These two poor (naive'?) kids went on a minimum 5-6 hour hike in a rugged jungle AND planned to go OFF TRAIL to a waterfall.  They carried ONE bottle of water, almost no food, no light source (flashlights), and no backup chargers or backup power source for their cell phones, no map or compass.  They packed as if planning a walk for a couple of miles to a museum in the middle of a city (and in THAT they would have not had enough water in a hot climate).  They weren't just un-prepared they were FRIGHTENINGLY unprepared.  I think you make a relatively simple tragedy into an overly complex one.  They got lost, and one probably injured, which people do ALL the time in much less difficult terrain) and could not find their way back to the trail.  That they survived as long as they did with ZERO jungle survival skills is actually remarkable.  There are always strange things and unexplained things with these disappearance mysteries.  Things that will never be explained.  They continually try 911 and 112 but NOT ONCE try their parents or their hostel home.  Who knows why?  They were probably scared out of their minds and in a complete panic.  Why did someone take a picture of the back of her head?  Maybe she got in the way of the camera when a picture was being taken.  Who knows.  And the silly rumor that the backpack was dry and everything found was neatly folded has been dispelled multiple times by investigators but keeps being repeated.  The contents were water logged and wet just as if they've been left out in the elements.  I'm so sorry for these poor girls and their families.  They died by misadventure.  ZERO evidence for homicide.
comments.author: @SamSpade-y5c

comments.text: No disrespect intended to these poor young ladies and what they went through. But I do believe there is a certain naivety that young people genuinely have - even those who may be somewhat well-traveled. When I was 20 years old, I spent my junior year of college in France. As my time overseas was coming to an end, I wanted to get in a few last travel moments. I took a ferry from France to Ireland, where I ended up meeting two French truck drivers aboard the ship. Long story short, they seemed like very friendly guys and seemed like people who would be cool to hang out with. They asked me what my plans were once I got to Ireland, and I told them I didn't have anything definite. They informed me that their plan was to drop off their shipment they were transporting (I think it was food), and then they had some down time before their next shipment.  They were planning on going fishing and asked me if I wanted to join them. The idea of fishing on some lake in Ireland with French truck drivers I had just met seemed like it would make for a fantastic story back home. I eagerly jumped at the offer and we began to make arrangements for how this was going to come together.  Needless to say, I had to go through a separate area for customs then they did since they were European and I was not and since they were making a delivery which probably also was a factor on where they had to go. We agreed that when we both went through our respective customs, we would meet up and be on our way for our fishing adventure. I was so bummed out when customs took me in a different direction and I was never able to meet up with these guys at all - so the plans never happened and I never saw them again. It was only in recent years that it dawned on me that it may have been a blessing in disguise that I didn't meet up with these two guys. At age 20, I was naive to the potential dangers. But now, I think about what might have happened if I had met with them and went off by myself with them. They easily could've done me harm and who would've ever known? The moral of the story:  Sometimes the things we think might be great ideas, might not really be so great if we stop and think about what could go wrong.

comments.text:
Cel tento ppad je matouc dungl protiklad. Zpotku jsem upednostoval teorii neist hry, ale nyn jsem pesvden o opaku.

daje z telefonu  nkolik pokus o voln na 911 a 112 a dva telefony zapnut a vypnut v prbhu 10 dn (vetn pouit aplikace pro poas) naznauj, e byly zoufale ztraceny. Dovolili by jim nosci pouvat telefony, i kdyby byla monost spojen jakkoli vzdlen? Vzdali by se dvou telefon, fotoapartu a 83 dolar, kter se naly v nalezenm batohu  co je v tto zbdaen oblasti znan vdlek? Ne.

Mnoz tvrdili, e je tm nemon se na stezce El Pianista ztratit, je tak dobe prolapan a znaen. Z fotografi z Canonu ale vme, e li nejmn hodinu pky za otoku Mirador, kolem kontinentlnho rozvod, a pokraovali minimln k prvn quebrad (potoku) pechzejcmu z kopce (msto posledn denn fotografie). S nejvt pravdpodobnost hledali "Skryt vodopd"  pojmenovan tak proto, e je obtn ho najt a vyaduje opustit hlavn stezku. Vodopdy mohou bt smrtelnou atrakc, kter lk turisty pokraovat za sv limity a moudr bod obratu.Dky vyetovn The Daily Beast vme, e tato oblast severn od Miradoru je bluditm matoucch kravskch stezek a ostruhovch stezek pouvanch mstnmi obyvateli v oblasti s hustou vegetac s astou oblanost a mlhou  ideln tern pro dezorientaci nezkuench, nebo dokonce zkuench turist. "Nkdy se tam i my ztratme," ekl Plinio Montenegro, star turistick prvodce v Boquete. Poznamenv, e se zde ztratila skupina 8 prvodc na vcvikov misi. Vede to k "jakmusi lesnmu lenstv," ekl Montenegro.

Uvdomili si, e jsou ztraceni a nemohou se vrtit do Boguete do 6:30 zpadu slunce, a uskutenili prvn nespn tsov voln na 911/112. Nizozemt vyetovatel se domnvali, e strvili prvn noc na mst, pak dal rno, bez kompasu nebo GPS. Pravdpodobn se uchlil ke starmu pslov: Nsledujte vodu z kopce, vede to k civilizaci. Prodrat se lesem bez maety a s jasnm smrem je tm nemon, navc s nebezpem, e lpnete na skrytho hada. Krom relativn ist cesty poskytuje eka tak hlavn zkladn potebu pro peit  pitnou vodu. Zd se, e se brodili po ece Culebra (ve skutenosti to byl spe potok ne eka) a pokraovali na sever a hledali pomoc. V tomto irokm dol byly z Miradoru vidt domorod stavby, ale vtina z nich byla oputna.

8. dubna zashla oblast prvn seznn boue. Zhadnch 90+ nonch fotografi pozench fotoapartem bhem 3 hodin t noci, vechny na stejnm mst, ukazuj kapky det odrejc zblesk. Kamera je ve vtin tchto zbr namena k nebi. Zd se, e se zoufale pokoueli nco signalizovat  akoli dn ptrac letadlo v noci neoperovalo, mohli slyet dopravn letadlo, nebo si to prost pedstavovali. V tu chvli u byli vyhladovl, vyerpan a v deliriu. Jeden nebo oba mohli v tomto okamiku utrpt zrann. Mohli spadnout z jednoho z nejistch opich most. A s detm nastupuje podchlazen a zoufalstv. O nkolik dn pozdji mon podlehli expozici.

Stav nkolika mlo nalezench kost (jedna vyblen fospohorovm zbarvenm, jedna s masem v ranm stdiu rozkladu) a nepotopen batoh a chybjc fotografie 509 podpoily teorii o nekal he. Ale v lnku pro Daily Beast Dr. Kathy Reichov poznamenv, e rozdln rychlost rozkladu a blen v mnoha mikroprostedch dungle nen neobvykl  i kdy tak poznamenv, e absence odenin nebo stop po predtorech na nalezench kostech je neobvykl.

Vechny tyto "anomlie" by mohly bt vysvtleny atypickmi, ale ne nemonmi prodnmi procesy. Kremerovy dnov ortky nebyly nalezeny hledn sloen na skle - byly nalezeny zachycen na vtvi stromu pod malm vodopdem. Batoh byl nalezen docela daleko po proudu od kost, s jednm funknm telefonem, druhm telefonem a fotoapartem pli mokrmi na to, aby fungovaly. Data byla u vech zskna forenzn vdou. Je mon, e nkte mstn obyvatel nali tento balek mnohem dve a nechali si ho jako neoekvanou vhru - dokud se hledn nezintenzivnilo a nebyla nabdnuta obrovsk odmna - pak byl znovu "nalezen" u eky.

Mnoz tvrd, e je velmi neobvykl, e dvky nebyly nalezeny masivnmi ptracmi tmy. Vme vak, e prvodce Feliciano provedl 2. dubna (den po jejich zmizen) spn slov ptrn po Miradoru a trochu dle, ale pln ptrac tmy byly nasazeny a 4. a 5. dubna a byly prohledny pouze dv trasy severn od Miradoru. Vtina ptracch tras vedla jin od Miradoru a smovala na vchod nebo na zpad, protoe se pedpokldalo, e dvky, stejn jako vtina turist, se neodvily pekroit vrchol Miradoru. Teprve pot, co byl batoh nalezen a pozdji zkontrolovny fotografie z fotoapartu Canon, byla zjitna skutenost, e dvky ly kolem Miradoru.Dvky mly nejmn ti cel dny na to, aby se pebrodily a sjely Culebru; Byli mlad, heallthy, a lid zachvcen panikou asto zabloudili mnohem, mnohem dl, ne ptrac tmy pedpokldaly. Co se te vrtulnk: prozkoumejte dostatek pbh o ztrtch/peit a asto narazte na toto svdectv peivch, podobn jako ve ve uvedenm ppad Brandona a Giny: "Vidl jsem vrtulnk, ale oni nikdy nevidli m." Od tch, kte peili a byli zachrnni jinmi prostedky. Jist mnoz, kte nikdy nepeili a nikdy nebyli nalezeni, mli stejnou zkuenost. Podvejte se na nkter leteck videa z dronu na Youtube o cel ece Culebra a uvdomte si, e vrtulnk by musel bt v perfektnm hlu, aby vidl dvky uvzl na skle s jejich chatrnm erveno-plastovm semaforem a npisem SOS. Koruny strom toho tolik zakrvaj.

V uritm okamiku se posedlost tmto ppadem (stovky lnk a vide online) zd ponkud dsiv. Jedinm smyslem pi pemlen o tom je nauit se nkolik ponauen:

Mentalita "jen jednodenn tra" zabila spoustu lid. Vdy s sebou noste nhradn obleen, vodu, kompas a FIRESTARTER pro ppad, e byste se ztratili. Tyto dv poloky jsou mal, levn a nev tm nic, ale mohou vm zachrnit ivot. Mete s sebou nosit GPS, ale nespolhejte se na nic napjenho bateriemi. MUS MT U SEBE KOMPAS a FIRESTARTER!! Ale ani kompas vm nepome, pokud nemte alespo obecnou mentln mapu ternu, ne vyrazte.

Nevyluuji pln monost neist hry, ale myslm si, e prohran scn je mnohem pravdpodobnj. Ale je zde pouen pro kadho  zejmna pro eny  kter se odv daleko od pomoci rychlho voln na 911: vezmte si psa nebo pepov sprej, stelnou zbra nebo alespo n. Nebute naivn: tam venku se pl tynoz a dvounoz predtoi, a to i v naich mstskch dunglch. Lep bt v bezpe, ne litovat.

DOVTEK: Letos (duben 2024) jsem el po stezkch v okol Boquete, vetn El Pianista. Jedn se o jeden z nejhorch monch tern, ve kterm se mete zorientovat. Velmi kopcovit, s nzkmi mraky viscmi mezi velmi vysokmi korunami strom a velmi hust porostlm podrostem. I kdybyste seli z vyznaen stezky, mli kompas a znali obecn smr zpt na stezku, stle by bylo extrmn obtn, ne-li nemon, se dostat ven, dokonce i s maetou. Je to tak drsn. I think the non-smiling photos are simply candid shots. No setup or warning a picture was about to be taken. Nothing sinister. The subject just wasn't prepared. The deleted picture could be of an embarrassing pose. Nudity perhaps (going for a swim?). One of those candid shots. If one of the girls began to suspect they might die and the camera found later, she might take the time to delete it, not wanting that to be widely seen. Or, the more sinister motive, someone who did not want their picture taken. The loss of night vision caused by the flash is easily overcome by just shutting your eyes when you push the button. It would seem a person would learn that pretty quickly. At the least close one eye. Cover it with your hand, as well as, closing it if possible.

comments.text: The rule of 3s in survival makes me really believe the abduction theory myself. On average a healthy human adult of any sex can only last about 3 minutes without oxygen (free divers are a rare exemption due to years of lung training/expanding exercises), 3 days without water or 3 weeks without food. Although these were educated women, they definitely dont come off like survivalists. They knew what to pack for a day hike but I doubt they would be able to source food and water in strange terrain long enough to survive multiple weeks. It makes me believe someone had to be either helping them stay alive in the bush, or they were held somewhere else and returned to the bush post mortem. That would explain how they didnt succumb to exposure, dehydration or starvation as well as how the remains somehow stayed so intact in such humid and rot inducing conditions. Also if Im not mistaken the area they went missing is somewhat near the entrance of the Durian Gap, which is notoriously overrun with criminal elements as well as being innately deadly due to its flora and fauna and extreme weather conditions. comments.text: What you say about the photo numbering presumes that 509 was taken and then deleted before another photo was taken. There is no logical reason to assume this. If you take 509 and then 510, then delete 509, then take a picture, that will be 511. The camera will not make another 509 until the highest numbered photo it has is 508. Reason for this is that when the camera saves a picture it simply looks up the highest numbered pic taken and does +1 as filename and saves. It does NOT look for 'missing' numbers in some series. Go ahead and try it your self if you have a camera. This is how every camera I've used and observed this particular aspect of has worked, when they use a numbering scheme, usually the filename is longer like MSCD01022002001 where MSCD is fixed, first 01 is day, 02 month, 2002 year, 001 number. The formats etc change but the logic has been the same across many camera brands.

comments.text:
Great theory, however there is one thing that doesn't add up to me. If F is really behind all this, how do you explain the fact that, while the girls were already missing, he was not physically present in the jungle? The day after the girls went missing, he was going around the city asking for information on where the girls were, he even went to the place where they were staying. I mean, if F chased the girls for about ten days, basically from the moment they started hiking until they stopped both turning on their phone and taking photos, which is presumably the moment in which they were already dead, F would have to follow them all the days the girls wandered in the jungle, even at night when there is zero visibility, to avoid losing sight of them. It seems really unlikely to me that F, or anyone else, was in the jungle for 10 days with the girls without ever losing sight of them for a second. It's very easy to lose sight of something or someone inside a jungle, where it is full of dense vegetation, and especially where visibility is zero at night. It also seems very unlikely to me that F started following the girls on April 1, when they started hiking, then over the course of 10 days he went to other places, and at the end of those 10 days he returned to the jungle where he is incredibly managed to find the girls and kill them. There are 2 options for me:

A) even though F may have something to do with all of this, it wasn't him who chased and killed the girls but someone else who followed them for all the 10 days they were in the jungle, without ever losing sight of them for a second. This theory it's seems very unlikely to me for numerous reasons, including the ones i listed above.

B) F (or whoever committed the crime) killed the girls on April 1st and then staged everything else. The photos, the 911 calls, the girls' phones turning on. All things he did to make it seem like the girls were still alive, when in reality they were already dead.

Regardless of what really happened in that jungle, and despite the fact that i don't scare easily and have read about hundreds of cases of unsolved mysteries, every time i think about this case i get chills all over my body.

comments.text:
1. There is a lot of misinformation in this case. Like how the backpack was found dry and clean..... No, it wasn't. It was very dirty and the experts were barely able to save the phones, so a case of misreporting by the media. 

Photo 509 has widely been reported to had to have been deleted by software (implying "the killer" must have manually deleted just this one photo)  but this is also not true. 
That particular phone will skip the number of a photo or video attempt if it gets corrupted due to, say, water getting on the phone when that particular image/video is taken, OR if the phone was dropped in water........ 
In other words, if the file is corrupted , it will skip to the next number... So photo 509 was corrupted , then the next photo taken was 510. 
(No need to invoke a killer permanently deleting a photo)

Kris' pelvis bone DID have rodent damage, it was not "undamaged" as was misreported. 
ALSO, the "other" bones were washed up from a nearby cemetery...
(No need to invoke a "killer" who has killed and dumped the bones of many different victims.)
***THE ROLLED UP SKIN WAS NOT LISSANE'S (another case of misreporting) 

all the calls to 112 mean the girls had the use of their phones and were trying to reach emergency services  (would murderers allow.them to call police?) 
... wouldn't the would-be-murderers just destroy their phones? (and not just delete 1 photo) Why would killers leave ANY evidence which could. potentially lead police to them?



2. ...I think the girls got hurt and or lost, OR BOTH, and then perished and eaten by scavengers. Their bones could have made their way far downstream/upstream due to flooding or heavy rain and that would explain why they were found so far away from the trail. 
No foul play needed.


3. In one "night photo" you can see toilet paper on a rock and there is a small mirror in the middle. 
It is , i think, an unmistakable sign of an attempt to be found by overhead aircraft
 (the toilet paper is laid out as a message, e.g.  "SOS" or something similar , while the mirror, which is  face up, was  placed there in hopes of overhead aircraft seeing a reflection) 


4. I'm 90% certain there was no foul play, but that is my opinion. 

The Panamanian verdict of a "hiking accident" is the only story that makes any sense to me.

Plus , most experts don't see any evidence of foul play. I don't either....

comments.text:
Have you ever seen photos taken by a child or observed a child playing with a locked phone? I strongly believe the girls encountered a missing child and possibly tried to comfort them by showing the child how to use the camera. It seems the child took the final photos of the women, indicated by the quality and distance, differing from the girls' usual selfies. This aligns with the possibility of the girls deleting a poor-quality photo the child took, or perhaps a more unsettling scenario where a photo of the child with the two women was deleted, potentially by authorities for unknown reasons.

Several pieces of evidence support the theory of the girls encountering a child:

1. Their direction indicated they were attempting to assist the child by heading north, likely trying to help the child return home.
2. A photo of Kris displaying a playful gesture suggests she was trying to make the child feel at ease while he is photographing her.
3. The photos only feature Kris, implying Lisanne might have been engaging with the child while photos were taken.
4. Subsequent photos bear resemblance to those typically taken by a child.

I believe the child might have been used as a lure, leading to the tragic end of the two women upon reaching the child's family or someone else. The child might have been rewarded with the women's belongings or simply retained them, including the camera and phones.

The child seemed to have limited knowledge about using the camera, likely taught by the two women. However, the child struggled with using the phones, inadvertently triggering emergency calls and entering incorrect PINs. Fascinated by the camera's functionality, the child randomly took photos, including one of Kris' deceased head. Subsequently, someone disposed of the bag, potentially an essential piece of evidence. Later, a villager discovered the bag and initially chose to keep it. However, upon learning of a potential reward, they opted to hand it to the authorities, considering the reward more valuable than the bag's contents.

comments.text: I agree with a lot of your analysis here. The one aspect I disagree with is that the girls were followed and that made them go further into the jungle. I don't think they would do that, knowing that their pursuer would eventually catch them and they would be even further from civilization. I think they were lured, most likely by the tour guide F., to walk past the usual turnaround point with the promise that he would meet them somewhere. He had been known to take tourists to his coffee farm, so this could be what he promised. But here's the other thing: Lisanne had $83 in her backpack. That's quite a bit of money for that area. If you look up Tour guide F, you'll find that he charges $40 for a specific tour that's on the opposite side of his coffee farm in Alto Romero. I think it's possible they were carrying that cash to pay him for another tour - an Ebike tour around a lake, specifically. He could have told them they could stay at his coffee farm and then go on to the Ebike tour that evening or perhaps the next day. They trusted him because he seemed like a well-respected guide, plus the fact that he's much older.
